    source: CORTEX_STEP_SOURCE_USER_EXPLICIT
  }
  user_input {
    user_response: "Build a hackathon MVP for an English accent classification system.\n\nProject concept:\nThe app analyzes a user\'s English pronunciation and estimates which English accent pattern it is closest to.\n\nImportant:\nDo NOT claim that the system predicts nationality directly.\nAccent is not the same as nationality.\nThe output must say \"closest accent pattern\" or \"accent group probability\", not \"you are from this country.\"\n\nExample output:\n- Korean-accented English: 68%\n- Japanese-accented English: 15%\n- Indian-accented English: 10%\n- American English: 5%\n- British English: 2%\n\nCore idea:\nExisting speech systems usually focus on \"what the user said\" through speech-to-text.\nOur system focuses on \"how the user pronounced it\" by analyzing acoustic features of the voice.\n\nTechnical goal:\nCreate a working prototype that can:\n1. Upload or record an English audio file.\n2. Preprocess the audio.\n3. Extract audio/acoustic features.\n4. Train or load an accent classifier.\n5. Predict the closest accent group with probability scores.\n6. Show the result in a simple web interface.\n\nRecommended stack:\n- Python\n- Streamlit for the UI\n- librosa or torchaudio for audio preprocessing\n- scikit-learn for a simple classifier\n- Optional: Hugging Face Wav2Vec2 / HuBERT for speech embeddings\n- joblib for saving/loading the trained classifier\n\nDo not build a huge deep learning system from scratch.\nFor the hackathon, use a practical approach:\nOption A:\nUse Wav2Vec2 or HuBERT as a pretrained feature extractor, then train a lightweight classifier such as Logistic Regression, RandomForest, or SVM.\n\nOption B:\nIf Wav2Vec2 is too heavy or difficult to run, use MFCC features from librosa and train a simple classifier.\n\nDataset structure:\nAssume the dataset folder is organized like this:\n\ndataset/\n  korean_accent/\n    korean_001.wav\n    korean_002.wav\n  japanese_accent/\n    japanese_001.wav\n    japanese_002.wav\n  indian_accent/\n    indian_001.wav\n    indian_002.wav\n  american_english/\n    american_001.wav\n    american_002.wav\n  british_english/\n    british_001.wav\n    british_002.wav\n\nEach folder name is the label.\n\nAudio preprocessing:\n- Convert audio to mono.\n- Resample to 16kHz.\n- Trim silence.\n- Normalize volume if possible.\n- Handle different file formats such as wav, mp3, m4a if possible.\n- If unsupported, show a clear error message.\n\nFeature extraction:\nImplement two modes:\n\n1. MFCC mode:\n- Extract MFCC features.\n- Compute mean and standard deviation across time.\n- Concatenate them into a fixed-length feature vector.\n\n2. Optional pretrained embedding mode:\n- Use Wav2Vec2 or HuBERT to extract speech embeddings.\n- Pool embeddings into a fixed-length vector.\n- Use this vector for classification.\n\nModel training:\n- Load all audio files from dataset folders.\n- Extract features for each audio file.\n- Train a classifier.\n- Split into train/test if enough data exists.\n- Show accuracy if possible.\n- Save the trained model to models/accent_classifier.joblib.\n- Save label encoder if needed.\n\nPrediction:\n- User uploads or records a new English audio file.\n- Apply the same preprocessing.\n- Extract the same features.\n- Load the trained classifier.\n- Predict probabilities.\n- Display ranked accent groups with confidence scores.\n\nUI requirements:\nCreate a Streamlit app with:\n1. Title:\n   \"AccentLens: English Accent Pattern Analyzer\"\n\n2. Short explanation:\n   \"This system does not predict nationality. It estimates which English accent pattern the pronunciation is closest to.\"\n\n3. Tabs or sections:\n   - Train model\n   - Predict accent\n   - About the method\n\n4. Train model section:\n   - Button: Train classifier from dataset folder\n   - Show number of files per label\n   - Show training result\n   - Save model\n\n5. Predict section:\n   - Audio file uploader\n   - Optional microphone recorder if easy\n   - Button: Analyze pronunciation\n   - Show probability chart or ranked result\n   - Show disclaimer\n\n6. About section:\n   Explain:\n   - Speech-to-text asks \"what did the user say?\"\n   - This system asks \"how did the user pronounce it?\"\n   - It analyzes acoustic features such as rhythm, pitch, stress, MFCC, or speech embeddings.\n   - It estimates accent pattern, not identity or nationality.\n\nSafety and ethics:\nAdd a clear disclaimer:\n- Accent does not perfectly represent nationality.\n- Results are probabilistic and may be wrong.\n- The system should be used for education or pronunciation feedback, not discrimination.\n- Do not use it for hiring, immigration, policing, or sensitive decisions.\n\nFiles to create:\n- app.py\n- train_model.py\n- predict.py\n- audio_utils.py\n- feature_extractor.py\n- requirements.txt\n- README.md\n- dataset/README.md\n- models/.gitkeep\n\nImplementation requirements:\n- Keep the code simple and hackathon-friendly.\n- Add comments explaining the pipeline.\n- Handle missing dataset folder gracefully.\n- Handle missing model file gracefully.\n- Do not hardcode private paths.\n- Do not include API keys.\n- Do not upload raw voice data anywhere.\n- Process audio locally in the prototype.\n\nREADME requirements:\nWrite a README that explains:\n1. Project overview\n2. Difference from normal speech recognition\n3. Dataset folder structure\n4. How to install dependencies\n5. How to train\n6. How to run Streamlit\n7. How to test prediction\n8. Limitations\n9. Ethics disclaimer\n\nPresentation explanation:\nAlso create a short English explanation for a professor:\n\n\"Our project is an English accent pattern classification system.\nMost speech systems focus on what the user said.\nOur system focuses on how the user pronounced it.\nWe extract acoustic features from English speech and classify which accent group the pronunciation is closest to.\nWe do not claim to predict nationality directly.\nInstead, we provide probability scores for accent patterns such as Korean-accented English, Japanese-accented English, Indian-accented English, American English, and British English.\"\n\nBefore coding:\nFirst inspect the current folder.\nThen propose a minimal implementation plan.\nAfter that, create the files.\nDo not over-engineer the project. \354\235\264\353\240\207\352\262\214\353\247\214\353\223\244\354\226\264\354\244\230"
    items {
      text: "Build a hackathon MVP for an English accent classification system.\n\nProject concept:\nThe app analyzes a user\'s English pronunciation and estimates which English accent pattern it is closest to.\n\nImportant:\nDo NOT claim that the system predicts nationality directly.\nAccent is not the same as nationality.\nThe output must say \"closest accent pattern\" or \"accent group probability\", not \"you are from this country.\"\n\nExample output:\n- Korean-accented English: 68%\n- Japanese-accented English: 15%\n- Indian-accented English: 10%\n- American English: 5%\n- British English: 2%\n\nCore idea:\nExisting speech systems usually focus on \"what the user said\" through speech-to-text.\nOur system focuses on \"how the user pronounced it\" by analyzing acoustic features of the voice.\n\nTechnical goal:\nCreate a working prototype that can:\n1. Upload or record an English audio file.\n2. Preprocess the audio.\n3. Extract audio/acoustic features.\n4. Train or load an accent classifier.\n5. Predict the closest accent group with probability scores.\n6. Show the result in a simple web interface.\n\nRecommended stack:\n- Python\n- Streamlit for the UI\n- librosa or torchaudio for audio preprocessing\n- scikit-learn for a simple classifier\n- Optional: Hugging Face Wav2Vec2 / HuBERT for speech embeddings\n- joblib for saving/loading the trained classifier\n\nDo not build a huge deep learning system from scratch.\nFor the hackathon, use a practical approach:\nOption A:\nUse Wav2Vec2 or HuBERT as a pretrained feature extractor, then train a lightweight classifier such as Logistic Regression, RandomForest, or SVM.\n\nOption B:\nIf Wav2Vec2 is too heavy or difficult to run, use MFCC features from librosa and train a simple classifier.\n\nDataset structure:\nAssume the dataset folder is organized like this:\n\ndataset/\n  korean_accent/\n    korean_001.wav\n    korean_002.wav\n  japanese_accent/\n    japanese_001.wav\n    japanese_002.wav\n  indian_accent/\n    indian_001.wav\n    indian_002.wav\n  american_english/\n    american_001.wav\n    american_002.wav\n  british_english/\n    british_001.wav\n    british_002.wav\n\nEach folder name is the label.\n\nAudio preprocessing:\n- Convert audio to mono.\n- Resample to 16kHz.\n- Trim silence.\n- Normalize volume if possible.\n- Handle different file formats such as wav, mp3, m4a if possible.\n- If unsupported, show a clear error message.\n\nFeature extraction:\nImplement two modes:\n\n1. MFCC mode:\n- Extract MFCC features.\n- Compute mean and standard deviation across time.\n- Concatenate them into a fixed-length feature vector.\n\n2. Optional pretrained embedding mode:\n- Use Wav2Vec2 or HuBERT to extract speech embeddings.\n- Pool embeddings into a fixed-length vector.\n- Use this vector for classification.\n\nModel training:\n- Load all audio files from dataset folders.\n- Extract features for each audio file.\n- Train a classifier.\n- Split into train/test if enough data exists.\n- Show accuracy if possible.\n- Save the trained model to models/accent_classifier.joblib.\n- Save label encoder if needed.\n\nPrediction:\n- User uploads or records a new English audio file.\n- Apply the same preprocessing.\n- Extract the same features.\n- Load the trained classifier.\n- Predict probabilities.\n- Display ranked accent groups with confidence scores.\n\nUI requirements:\nCreate a Streamlit app with:\n1. Title:\n   \"AccentLens: English Accent Pattern Analyzer\"\n\n2. Short explanation:\n   \"This system does not predict nationality. It estimates which English accent pattern the pronunciation is closest to.\"\n\n3. Tabs or sections:\n   - Train model\n   - Predict accent\n   - About the method\n\n4. Train model section:\n   - Button: Train classifier from dataset folder\n   - Show number of files per label\n   - Show training result\n   - Save model\n\n5. Predict section:\n   - Audio file uploader\n   - Optional microphone recorder if easy\n   - Button: Analyze pronunciation\n   - Show probability chart or ranked result\n   - Show disclaimer\n\n6. About section:\n   Explain:\n   - Speech-to-text asks \"what did the user say?\"\n   - This system asks \"how did the user pronounce it?\"\n   - It analyzes acoustic features such as rhythm, pitch, stress, MFCC, or speech embeddings.\n   - It estimates accent pattern, not identity or nationality.\n\nSafety and ethics:\nAdd a clear disclaimer:\n- Accent does not perfectly represent nationality.\n- Results are probabilistic and may be wrong.\n- The system should be used for education or pronunciation feedback, not discrimination.\n- Do not use it for hiring, immigration, policing, or sensitive decisions.\n\nFiles to create:\n- app.py\n- train_model.py\n- predict.py\n- audio_utils.py\n- feature_extractor.py\n- requirements.txt\n- README.md\n- dataset/README.md\n- models/.gitkeep\n\nImplementation requirements:\n- Keep the code simple and hackathon-friendly.\n- Add comments explaining the pipeline.\n- Handle missing dataset folder gracefully.\n- Handle missing model file gracefully.\n- Do not hardcode private paths.\n- Do not include API keys.\n- Do not upload raw voice data anywhere.\n- Process audio locally in the prototype.\n\nREADME requirements:\nWrite a README that explains:\n1. Project overview\n2. Difference from normal speech recognition\n3. Dataset folder structure\n4. How to install dependencies\n5. How to train\n6. How to run Streamlit\n7. How to test prediction\n8. Limitations\n9. Ethics disclaimer\n\nPresentation explanation:\nAlso create a short English explanation for a professor:\n\n\"Our project is an English accent pattern classification system.\nMost speech systems focus on what the user said.\nOur system focuses on how the user pronounced it.\nWe extract acoustic features from English speech and classify which accent group the pronunciation is closest to.\nWe do not claim to predict nationality directly.\nInstead, we provide probability scores for accent patterns such as Korean-accented English, Japanese-accented English, Indian-accented English, American English, and British English.\"\n\nBefore coding:\nFirst inspect the current folder.\nThen propose a minimal implementation plan.\nAfter that, create the files.\nDo not over-engineer the project. \354\235\264\353\240\207\352\262\214\353\247\214\353\223\244\354\226\264\354\244\230"
