  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Prioritizing File Creation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on creating the Python files, but the prompt\'s focus on removing API key exposure in addition to building a hackathon MVP has brought up a new question. Do I address the API removal in the existing Node app, or explain that the new Python app addresses this?\n\n\n**Generating Python Files**\n\nI\'m now generating the necessary Python files for the application. First, `requirements.txt` to install the dependencies. Then, I\'m working on `audio_utils.py` to handle audio loading, pre-processing (mono conversion, resampling, trimming silence, volume normalization), and feature extraction, preparing the audio data for analysis. The function also supports file-like objects for easier integration.\n\n\n**Defining Feature Extraction**\n\nI\'ve completed `audio_utils.py`, ensuring robust audio preprocessing including normalization and error handling. I\'m now writing `feature_extractor.py`, focusing on MFCC feature extraction with mean and standard deviation calculation for fixed-length vector generation. The `extract_mfcc_features` function is implemented and handles edge cases such as empty audio.\n\n\n**Implementing Classifier Training**\n\nI\'m now integrating the training components. I\'m building `train_classifier.py`. It uses `audio_utils.py` and `feature_extractor.py` to handle data loading, preprocessing, and feature extraction. The classifier, a Random Forest, is being implemented with train/test splits. I\'m also including label encoding, and saving the model with Joblib, along with its encoder. I will implement error handling.\n\n\n**Processing Data Preparation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on integrating the data loading, preprocessing, feature extraction, and label encoding steps within the `train_classifier.py` script. I\'m dynamically handling audio files within specified class directories and skipping invalid or corrupt files, with error handling. This is ensuring robust data handling for training. Finally, I\'m setting up label encoding, with the necessary train/test split.\n\n\n**Evaluating Model Performance**\n\nI\'ve completed the model training and evaluation within `train_classifier.py`. I\'ve implemented a train/test split, handling cases with insufficient data by training on all available data. A Random Forest classifier is used, with accuracy computed on the test set. The model and label encoder are being saved using Joblib. The code also includes error handling for more robustness.\n\n\n**Defining Prediction Logic**\n\nI\'m now building the `AccentPredictor` class. This class handles model loading, using a saved classifier from `joblib` and label encoder. The `load_model` method checks for model and encoder file existence and loads them. The `predict` function loads audio, extracts features, and uses the model to predict the accent. I\'m adding a robust error check for model absence, throwing a `ValueError` if the model isn\'t trained or missing.\n\n\n**Refining Prediction Probabilities**\n\nI am now refining the `predict` function within the `AccentPredictor` class. This involves reshaping the features for prediction. I\'m extracting probabilities for each class from the classifier output and getting the class names. I\'m generating a sorted list of class names and their probabilities and returning that result.\n\n\n**Integrating Streamlit UI**\n\nI\'m now integrating the Streamlit user interface to upload audio and trigger the accent analysis. I\'m adding a file uploader for `.wav`, `.mp3`, and `.m4a` files. The audio is displayed using `st.audio`. A button labeled \"Analyze Pronunciation\" triggers the prediction. A progress spinner provides feedback during the analysis.\n\n\\n\\n\n\nThe analysis incorporates the `AccentPredictor` for predictions. On completion, a success message displays, and the top accent patterns, with probabilities, are rendered in a bulleted list using pandas dataframes for charting, providing a user-friendly display of results, with progress bars. The code also includes error handling using `try...except` blocks and a spinner.\n\n\n**Adding Dataset Functionality**\n\nI\'m now integrating dataset loading and model training into the Streamlit app. I\'ve added a second tab for classifier training. I\'m dynamically checking the \"dataset\" directory for subdirectories, which are assumed to be class names, reporting the number of files per class. I\'ve also added a disclaimer emphasizing that the results are probabilistic and should be used for educational purposes.\n\n\n**Describing App Functionality**\n\nI\'m now describing the app\'s functionality in the \"About the Method\" section. I\'m focusing on the core difference between speech-to-text and the accent analysis. This section outlines how the system uses acoustic features such as rhythm, pitch, stress, and MFCC to extract features.\n\n\n**Defining Project Context**\n\nI\'m now integrating the safety and ethics considerations into the app\'s documentation. I\'m carefully explaining that accent patterns don\'t perfectly represent nationality or identity. I\'m also emphasizing that the results are probabilistic and may be incorrect, and highlighting that the tool should be used for educational purposes, not for any form of discrimination. I\'m adding a `README.md` to describe the accent analysis focus, and its differences from speech-to-text.\n\n\n**Documenting Model Usage**\n\nI\'m now documenting the model usage. I\'m focusing on providing users with clear instructions on how to use the model, by explaining the dataset folder structure, how to install dependencies, how to train the model, how to run the Streamlit app, and how to test the predictions. I\'m also clearly stating limitations, such as dataset dependency.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 23
      nanos: 712625417
    }
