  user_input {
    user_response: "Build the data analysis and model training pipeline for an English accent pattern classification MVP.\n\nProject concept:\nThe system analyzes a user\'s English pronunciation and estimates which English accent pattern it is closest to.\n\nImportant:\nDo NOT claim to predict nationality directly.\nAccent is not the same as nationality.\nThe system should output probability scores for accent groups, such as:\n- Korean-accented English\n- Japanese-accented English\n- Indian-accented English\n- American English\n- British English\n\nThe key idea:\nExisting speech recognition systems focus on \"what the user said.\"\nOur system focuses on \"how the user pronounced it.\"\n\nGoal:\nCreate a complete pipeline for:\n1. Dataset inspection\n2. Audio preprocessing\n3. Feature extraction\n4. Model training\n5. Model evaluation\n6. Model saving/loading\n7. Accent prediction for new audio\n8. Optional post-learning update after user confirmation\n\nRecommended stack:\n- Python\n- librosa\n- numpy\n- pandas\n- scikit-learn\n- matplotlib\n- joblib\n- Streamlit if UI integration is needed\n\nDataset structure:\nAssume the dataset folder looks like this:\n\ndataset/\n  korean_accent/\n    korean_001.wav\n    korean_002.wav\n  japanese_accent/\n    japanese_001.wav\n    japanese_002.wav\n  indian_accent/\n    indian_001.wav\n    indian_002.wav\n  american_english/\n    american_001.wav\n    american_002.wav\n  british_english/\n    british_001.wav\n    british_002.wav\n\nEach folder name is the label.\n\nMain rule:\nDo not train from speech-to-text output.\nDo not convert the audio to text for classification.\nFor accent classification, use the sound itself.\nThe model must learn from acoustic features.\n\nPipeline:\n\n1. Dataset inspection\nCreate a script that scans the dataset folder and reports:\n- number of audio files per accent label\n- total number of files\n- average audio duration per label\n- minimum and maximum duration\n- sample rate distribution\n- class imbalance warning\n- unreadable or corrupted files\n\nIf one label has much more data than others, print a warning:\n\"Class imbalance detected. The model may become biased toward labels with more samples.\"\n\n2. Audio preprocessing\nFor every audio file:\n- load audio safely\n- convert to mono\n- resample to 16kHz\n- trim leading and trailing silence\n- normalize volume if possible\n- reject files that are too short\n- handle wav, mp3, and m4a if possible\n- show a clear error message for unsupported files\n\n3. Feature extraction\nImplement MFCC-based feature extraction first because it is simple and suitable for a hackathon MVP.\n\nFor each audio file:\n- extract MFCC features using librosa\n- use around 13 to 40 MFCC coefficients\n- compute mean across time\n- compute standard deviation across time\n- optionally compute delta MFCC and delta-delta MFCC\n- concatenate these into one fixed-length feature vector\n\nThe output should be:\nX = feature vectors\ny = accent labels\n\n4. Optional feature mode\nIf time allows, add a second feature extraction mode:\n- Wav2Vec2 or HuBERT embeddings from a pretrained model\n- pool embeddings into a fixed-length vector\n- train the same classifier on those embeddings\n\nBut do not make Wav2Vec2 required for the first MVP.\nMFCC + RandomForest should work as the default.\n\n5. Model training\nTrain a classifier using the extracted features.\n\nStart with:\n- RandomForestClassifier\n- LogisticRegression\n- SVM as optional\n\nUse train/test split.\n\nImportant:\nIf speaker IDs are available, split by speaker instead of by file.\nIf speaker IDs are not available, add a warning:\n\"Speaker-level split is recommended. File-level split may overestimate accuracy if the same speaker appears in both train and test.\"\n\n6. Model evaluation\nShow:\n- accuracy\n- classification report\n- confusion matrix\n- per-label precision, recall, and F1-score\n\nSave evaluation results to:\nreports/evaluation_report.txt\n\nSave confusion matrix image to:\nreports/confusion_matrix.png\n\n7. Model saving\nSave the trained model to:\nmodels/accent_classifier.joblib\n\nSave the label encoder or class list to:\nmodels/labels.joblib\n\nAlso save basic model metadata to:\nmodels/model_metadata.json\n\nMetadata should include:\n- feature type\n- sample rate\n- MFCC count\n- labels\n- training date\n- number of samples per label\n- test accuracy\n\n8. Prediction\nCreate a prediction function that:\n- loads a new audio file\n- applies the same preprocessing\n- extracts the same features\n- loads the trained classifier\n- returns ranked probability scores\n\nOutput example:\n{\n  \"top_prediction\": \"korean_accent\",\n  \"probabilities\": {\n    \"korean_accent\": 0.68,\n    \"japanese_accent\": 0.15,\n    \"indian_accent\": 0.10,\n    \"american_english\": 0.05,\n    \"british_english\": 0.02\n  }\n}\n\nThe user-facing message must be:\n\"Your pronunciation is closest to Korean-accented English.\"\n\nDo not say:\n\"You are Korean.\"\n\n9. Post-learning update\nAdd a simple optional post-learning workflow.\n\nWhen the system predicts an accent, the user can confirm or correct the result.\n\nExample:\nPrediction: Korean-accented English\nUser correction: Japanese-accented English\n\nIf the user confirms consent:\n- do not store raw audio by default\n- store only the extracted feature vector and corrected label\n- save it to:\n  feedback/confirmed_features.csv\n\nThis allows later retraining without keeping raw voice files.\n\nAdd a comment:\n\"This is a privacy-aware post-learning approach. The system does not immediately learn from raw voice. It stores processed features only after user confirmation.\"\n\n10. Files to create\nCreate the following files:\n\naudio_utils.py\n- load_audio()\n- preprocess_audio()\n\nfeature_extractor.py\n- extract_mfcc_features()\n- optional extract_wav2vec_features() placeholder\n\nanalyze_dataset.py\n- scan dataset\n- print statistics\n- save dataset report\n\ntrain_model.py\n- load dataset\n- extract features\n- train classifier\n- evaluate\n- save model\n\npredict.py\n- load model\n- predict accent probabilities for a new audio file\n\npost_learning.py\n- save confirmed feature vectors and corrected labels\n\napp.py\n- optional Streamlit UI\n- train model button\n- upload audio file\n- analyze pronunciation button\n- show probability ranking\n- show disclaimer\n\nrequirements.txt\nREADME.md\n\n11. Streamlit UI requirements\nIf creating app.py, include:\n\nTitle:\n\"AccentLens: English Accent Pattern Analyzer\"\n\nDisclaimer:\n\"This system does not predict nationality. It estimates which English accent pattern the pronunciation is closest to. Results are probabilistic and may be wrong.\"\n\nSections:\n- Dataset Analysis\n- Train Model\n- Predict Accent\n- Post-Learning Feedback\n- About\n\nPrediction UI:\n- upload audio file\n- button: Analyze Pronunciation\n- show ranked probability results\n- allow user to confirm or correct the prediction\n- save confirmed features only if the user consents\n\n12. Ethics and safety\nAdd clear warnings:\n- Accent does not perfectly represent nationality.\n- Do not use this system for hiring, immigration, policing, or sensitive decisions.\n- The system is for education, language learning, and pronunciation feedback.\n- Results may be inaccurate due to microphone quality, noise, speaker variation, and dataset bias.\n\n13. README requirements\nREADME should explain:\n- project overview\n- difference from normal speech recognition\n- dataset folder structure\n- how to install dependencies\n- how to run dataset analysis\n- how to train the model\n- how to run prediction\n- how post-learning works\n- limitations\n- ethics disclaimer\n\n14. Implementation constraints\n- Keep code simple and hackathon-friendly.\n- Do not over-engineer.\n- Do not require cloud services.\n- Do not require API keys.\n- Do not upload audio anywhere.\n- Process locally.\n- Handle errors gracefully.\n- Add comments so beginners can understand the pipeline.\n\nBefore coding:\nFirst inspect the current project folder.\nThen propose a minimal implementation plan.\nAfter that, create the files."
    items {
      text: "Build the data analysis and model training pipeline for an English accent pattern classification MVP.\n\nProject concept:\nThe system analyzes a user\'s English pronunciation and estimates which English accent pattern it is closest to.\n\nImportant:\nDo NOT claim to predict nationality directly.\nAccent is not the same as nationality.\nThe system should output probability scores for accent groups, such as:\n- Korean-accented English\n- Japanese-accented English\n- Indian-accented English\n- American English\n- British English\n\nThe key idea:\nExisting speech recognition systems focus on \"what the user said.\"\nOur system focuses on \"how the user pronounced it.\"\n\nGoal:\nCreate a complete pipeline for:\n1. Dataset inspection\n2. Audio preprocessing\n3. Feature extraction\n4. Model training\n5. Model evaluation\n6. Model saving/loading\n7. Accent prediction for new audio\n8. Optional post-learning update after user confirmation\n\nRecommended stack:\n- Python\n- librosa\n- numpy\n- pandas\n- scikit-learn\n- matplotlib\n- joblib\n- Streamlit if UI integration is needed\n\nDataset structure:\nAssume the dataset folder looks like this:\n\ndataset/\n  korean_accent/\n    korean_001.wav\n    korean_002.wav\n  japanese_accent/\n    japanese_001.wav\n    japanese_002.wav\n  indian_accent/\n    indian_001.wav\n    indian_002.wav\n  american_english/\n    american_001.wav\n    american_002.wav\n  british_english/\n    british_001.wav\n    british_002.wav\n\nEach folder name is the label.\n\nMain rule:\nDo not train from speech-to-text output.\nDo not convert the audio to text for classification.\nFor accent classification, use the sound itself.\nThe model must learn from acoustic features.\n\nPipeline:\n\n1. Dataset inspection\nCreate a script that scans the dataset folder and reports:\n- number of audio files per accent label\n- total number of files\n- average audio duration per label\n- minimum and maximum duration\n- sample rate distribution\n- class imbalance warning\n- unreadable or corrupted files\n\nIf one label has much more data than others, print a warning:\n\"Class imbalance detected. The model may become biased toward labels with more samples.\"\n\n2. Audio preprocessing\nFor every audio file:\n- load audio safely\n- convert to mono\n- resample to 16kHz\n- trim leading and trailing silence\n- normalize volume if possible\n- reject files that are too short\n- handle wav, mp3, and m4a if possible\n- show a clear error message for unsupported files\n\n3. Feature extraction\nImplement MFCC-based feature extraction first because it is simple and suitable for a hackathon MVP.\n\nFor each audio file:\n- extract MFCC features using librosa\n- use around 13 to 40 MFCC coefficients\n- compute mean across time\n- compute standard deviation across time\n- optionally compute delta MFCC and delta-delta MFCC\n- concatenate these into one fixed-length feature vector\n\nThe output should be:\nX = feature vectors\ny = accent labels\n\n4. Optional feature mode\nIf time allows, add a second feature extraction mode:\n- Wav2Vec2 or HuBERT embeddings from a pretrained model\n- pool embeddings into a fixed-length vector\n- train the same classifier on those embeddings\n\nBut do not make Wav2Vec2 required for the first MVP.\nMFCC + RandomForest should work as the default.\n\n5. Model training\nTrain a classifier using the extracted features.\n\nStart with:\n- RandomForestClassifier\n- LogisticRegression\n- SVM as optional\n\nUse train/test split.\n\nImportant:\nIf speaker IDs are available, split by speaker instead of by file.\nIf speaker IDs are not available, add a warning:\n\"Speaker-level split is recommended. File-level split may overestimate accuracy if the same speaker appears in both train and test.\"\n\n6. Model evaluation\nShow:\n- accuracy\n- classification report\n- confusion matrix\n- per-label precision, recall, and F1-score\n\nSave evaluation results to:\nreports/evaluation_report.txt\n\nSave confusion matrix image to:\nreports/confusion_matrix.png\n\n7. Model saving\nSave the trained model to:\nmodels/accent_classifier.joblib\n\nSave the label encoder or class list to:\nmodels/labels.joblib\n\nAlso save basic model metadata to:\nmodels/model_metadata.json\n\nMetadata should include:\n- feature type\n- sample rate\n- MFCC count\n- labels\n- training date\n- number of samples per label\n- test accuracy\n\n8. Prediction\nCreate a prediction function that:\n- loads a new audio file\n- applies the same preprocessing\n- extracts the same features\n- loads the trained classifier\n- returns ranked probability scores\n\nOutput example:\n{\n  \"top_prediction\": \"korean_accent\",\n  \"probabilities\": {\n    \"korean_accent\": 0.68,\n    \"japanese_accent\": 0.15,\n    \"indian_accent\": 0.10,\n    \"american_english\": 0.05,\n    \"british_english\": 0.02\n  }\n}\n\nThe user-facing message must be:\n\"Your pronunciation is closest to Korean-accented English.\"\n\nDo not say:\n\"You are Korean.\"\n\n9. Post-learning update\nAdd a simple optional post-learning workflow.\n\nWhen the system predicts an accent, the user can confirm or correct the result.\n\nExample:\nPrediction: Korean-accented English\nUser correction: Japanese-accented English\n\nIf the user confirms consent:\n- do not store raw audio by default\n- store only the extracted feature vector and corrected label\n- save it to:\n  feedback/confirmed_features.csv\n\nThis allows later retraining without keeping raw voice files.\n\nAdd a comment:\n\"This is a privacy-aware post-learning approach. The system does not immediately learn from raw voice. It stores processed features only after user confirmation.\"\n\n10. Files to create\nCreate the following files:\n\naudio_utils.py\n- load_audio()\n- preprocess_audio()\n\nfeature_extractor.py\n- extract_mfcc_features()\n- optional extract_wav2vec_features() placeholder\n\nanalyze_dataset.py\n- scan dataset\n- print statistics\n- save dataset report\n\ntrain_model.py\n- load dataset\n- extract features\n- train classifier\n- evaluate\n- save model\n\npredict.py\n- load model\n- predict accent probabilities for a new audio file\n\npost_learning.py\n- save confirmed feature vectors and corrected labels\n\napp.py\n- optional Streamlit UI\n- train model button\n- upload audio file\n- analyze pronunciation button\n- show probability ranking\n- show disclaimer\n\nrequirements.txt\nREADME.md\n\n11. Streamlit UI requirements\nIf creating app.py, include:\n\nTitle:\n\"AccentLens: English Accent Pattern Analyzer\"\n\nDisclaimer:\n\"This system does not predict nationality. It estimates which English accent pattern the pronunciation is closest to. Results are probabilistic and may be wrong.\"\n\nSections:\n- Dataset Analysis\n- Train Model\n- Predict Accent\n- Post-Learning Feedback\n- About\n\nPrediction UI:\n- upload audio file\n- button: Analyze Pronunciation\n- show ranked probability results\n- allow user to confirm or correct the prediction\n- save confirmed features only if the user consents\n\n12. Ethics and safety\nAdd clear warnings:\n- Accent does not perfectly represent nationality.\n- Do not use this system for hiring, immigration, policing, or sensitive decisions.\n- The system is for education, language learning, and pronunciation feedback.\n- Results may be inaccurate due to microphone quality, noise, speaker variation, and dataset bias.\n\n13. README requirements\nREADME should explain:\n- project overview\n- difference from normal speech recognition\n- dataset folder structure\n- how to install dependencies\n- how to run dataset analysis\n- how to train the model\n- how to run prediction\n- how post-learning works\n- limitations\n- ethics disclaimer\n\n14. Implementation constraints\n- Keep code simple and hackathon-friendly.\n- Do not over-engineer.\n- Do not require cloud services.\n- Do not require API keys.\n- Do not upload audio anywhere.\n- Process locally.\n- Handle errors gracefully.\n- Add comments so beginners can understand the pipeline.\n\nBefore coding:\nFirst inspect the current project folder.\nThen propose a minimal implementation plan.\nAfter that, create the files."
    }
  }
}
